================================================================================
5. POSITIVE OBSERVATIONS
================================================================================

  + Build succeeds cleanly — `cargo build --release` compiles without errors.
    Only 3 dead-code warnings exist (all suppressed in this session).

  + Cargo.lock is committed — reproducible builds are guaranteed across
    developer, CI, and release environments. (Fixed in a previous audit.)

  + Comprehensive test coverage — every module has dedicated unit tests;
    integration tests cover CLI flags, pipeline behaviour, and edge cases.
    Tests are environment-aware (skip when pandoc/tectonic not installed).

  + Dependency validation is excellent — pandoc is always checked; tectonic
    only when PDF is requested. Error messages include install links.

  + Error messages are user-friendly — every error path provides context
    (what failed, why, and how to fix it). Errors chain correctly via anyhow.

  + Parallel output rendering — rayon is used to render multiple output
    formats concurrently. Progress bars (indicatif) give clear feedback.

  + Two-level caching is implemented — transform results are cached by input
    hash; render results are cached by content+format+template hash. Skipping
    unchanged outputs reduces redundant pandoc invocations.

  + Cross-compilation is configured — Cross.toml enables `cross build` for
    aarch64 and x86_64 MUSL targets. Distribution binaries can be built
    reproducibly.

  + Watch mode is implemented — notify + debounce watcher re-runs builds on
    file change with configurable debounce delay.

  + Architecture is clean and extensible — OutputStrategy, Transform, and
    PipelineStep are all trait-based. Adding new formats or transforms
    requires only implementing the appropriate trait.

  + Input format compatibility matrix is explicit — the compat module
    encodes which input → output combinations are valid. Unsupported
    combinations produce clear, user-facing error messages.

  + Dry-run mode works end to end — no files are written and no external
    commands are invoked; the pipeline logs what it would do.

